  <glossary>
  <definition id="def-00001"><term>antithyroid drugs</term> <meaning>inhibit the thyroid hormone so that the body can maintain normal thyroid homeostasis</meaning></definition>
  <definition id="def-00002"><term>goiter</term> <meaning>an abnormal enlargement of the thyroid gland</meaning></definition>
  <definition id="def-00003"><term>iodine</term> <meaning>a mineral that the body needs to produce thyroid hormones</meaning></definition>
  <definition id="def-00004"><term>iodotyrosine</term> <meaning>an iodo-derivative of tyrosine that acts as an intermediary in the biosynthesis of thyroid hormone</meaning></definition>
  <definition id="def-00005"><term>organification</term> <meaning>the biochemical process that takes place in the thyroid gland, involving the incorporation of iodine into thyroglobulin for the production of thyroid hormone</meaning></definition>
  <definition id="def-00006"><term>thyroglobulin</term> <meaning>a protein present in the thyroid gland from which thyroid hormones are synthesized</meaning></definition>
  <definition id="def-00007"><term>thyroid drugs</term> <meaning>drugs that replace the thyroid hormone so that the body can maintain its normal function</meaning></definition>
  </glossary>
